A candidate in the just-concluded KCPE exam is among 11 people charged with examination malpractices yesterday.The 14-year-old faces an offence of copying an exam contrary to Section 32 (e) of the Kenya National Examination Council Act 29 of 2012, Chapter 225.The 11 appeared before Keroka resident magistrate Njoki Kahara. The 11, among them a head teacher, an exam supervisor and invigilators, allegedly committed the offences at St Andrews Kaggwa Boys Primary School in Nyamira county on Tuesday. The pupil s parents were present in court. He denied the charges. According to the charge sheet, the candidate was found with a pre-marked English exam answer sheet on Tuesday. He was released on Sh100,000 bond and Sh50,000 bail. Law-abiding The head teacher, supervisor and invigilators faced separate charges of aiding and abetting the candidate to copy the paper, contrary to Section 40 of the same law, and another conspiracy to commit a felony contrary to Section 393 of the Penal Code. They denied the charges.They are head teacher Joseph Nyachieo, supervisor Caren Nyakeriga and invigilators Agnes Machini, Caren Okenyuri, Diana Nyanchoka, Gladys Aruga, James Atuti, James Onsese, Joyce Mirera and Risper Omae. Their lawyer Okong o Omogeni asked the court to release them on reasonable bail, saying they are teachers, hence not a flight risk. They have cooperated with investigating officers. They are law-abiding citizens whose salary scale is around Sh25,000. I pray the court sets favourable conditions for bonds and cash bails, Omogeni said. They were each released on Sh300,00 bond with a similar surety, and Sh100,000 bail. The case will be mentioned on November 17 and heard on April 3 next year.